g` code somehow.\n   252\t\n   253\tPossible linkage paths:\n   254\t\n   255\t- short term: depend on the GitButler repository as a pinned Cargo git\n   256\t  dependency and import the `but-agentlog` package\n   257\t- local development: use a path dependency from Forge to a local GitButler\n   258\t  checkout\n   259\t- longer term: make `but-agentlog` publishable, or split a smaller\n   260\t  `but-agentlog` read/projection\n[TRUNCATED]\nf name used for the fetched metadata is an implementation\n   389\tdetail between the GitMeta helper and `but-agentlog`. The important contract is\n   390\tthat snapshot generation reads from the resolved metadata OID, not from a moving\n   391\tref that can change mid-request.\n   392\t\n   393\t## Relationship Model\n   394\t\n   395\tOne pull request may relate to many sessions. One session may relate to many\n   396\tpull requests or branches.\n   397\t\n   398\tThe durable object remains the project-scoped session. Pull requests, reviews,\n   399\tand branches should reference session or turn keys; they should not own copies\n   400\tof transcript records. Change targets remain available in `but-agentlog`, but\n   401\tAgent Trail v1 does not query them.\n   402\t\n   403\tThe first Agent Trail implementation can start from:\n   404\t\n   405\t1. pull request number as a `review` target, such as\n   406\t   `gitbutler-review:13936`\n   407\t2. PR head branch as a branch target, if GitHub metadata is available\n   408\t3. `but-agentlog` related-session lookup across the review and branch targets\n   409\t4. verified related turns from stored observed targets\n   410\t5. bounded transcript hydration for selected turns\n   411\t\n   412\t## Review Experience\n   413\t\n   414\tThe default view should be compact and review-focused.\n   415\t\n   416\tShow:\n   417\t\n   418\t- what the human asked the agent to do\n   419\t- what the agent said it changed\n   420\t- what commands or tools it ran\n   421\t- what validation passed